8.5.19  2:01 pm   With regards to the "Click static text" issue, it might be that the text itself doesn't have a clickable action associated with it. Button components have 2 visible elements to it, the outer bounding box, and the text inside it. In typical usage, a mouse click within the bounding box triggers the action of the button. The click action can be associated with the inclosed text, the bounding box, or both. If the text has no clickable action, it seems reasonable that "missing value" would be returned, even if it is able to find the text itself. Automator may have incorrectly assumed the click action was associated with the text instead of the bounding box, or if your program is particularly nasty, the click action may be just associated with a certain x y position on the screen. Somehow you have to get the name of the actual button box, and script a click action on that box rather than the text.

     i've looked everywhere in "accessibility inspector", suspecting that it may be hidden neatly behind something. but i don't think you can move anything out of the way in accessibility inspector. but, i've found some pretty thorough scripts that extrapolate every possible UI element (or so they say ....) and gone through every single one of them and not found the secret button i'm looking for. so i don't know

      If it is possible to script a click action to a x y positio n, you c an hopefully skip this mess,

     yes, i can do that

      although as you mentioned previously you would need to watch window size/position or create different scripts for different work environments. It might be possible to script window positioning as well.

     yes, i do that all the time. and that does work here. but for various reasons i am definitely looking for something snappier in this case. i just really think there is a snappier way. actually i think there's some even better ways with jxa or swift or something to get way more internal and skip the UI, but i can't find ANY inspectors or recorders, or any way to actually learn what i'm going for

     

Note: I probably should mention I have computer experience but not with Mac, so this is all "informed" guessing.

     in many cases when there's no keyboard shortcut and no menu item, it often is accessible by applescript. but there is a specific kind of situation where clicking something in real life makes something happen, and the automator recorder claims that what i did can be translated to applescript as "click static text", and yet putting that into applescript yields "missing value." in approximately half of these situations, the parent item is "row", and if that's the case, i have found a secret solution of saying "select row."

      Weird question on my part, but have u made sure to have only 1 instance of whatever it is you're manipulating?

     yes

      static usually means theres only 1 instance of that value so idk if having several might trip it out,

     actually in all these cases there is a number after it, "static text 1" or "static text 2". getting rid of the others would be impossible because it's usually clicking something in a list, or clicking amongst a set of 'buttons', but it would be the only one with that number (i assume)
